description.plain:
“Why Don’t You Come On” is an immediate earworm, a positive plea for peace and togetherness, exalted by the twin vocals of the Texan teen sensation Khalid and the L.A. wunderkind Empress Of.

Khalid plays headliner here: His voice is a gritty baritone that lays down the track’s backbone, making room for Empress Of’s saintly high notes. DJDS possess the confidence and playfulness to juxtapose these two starkly opposing styles with ease: the minimal drum and synth rhythms that skitter around them complement both Khalid’s yearning voice and Empress Of’s angelic flow.

“Why Don’t You Come On” is an ideal cap to a scorching night, its beat as refreshing as a blast of cool air.

A B-side from her 2015 album Me, “Woman is a Word” is a woke-as-hell feminist slapper.

In a Saint Heron video, Rodriguez explains that “making music and being a woman are one and one” to her:

My family makes me feel like a woman and my mom is the strongest person I know – man or woman – in my life, so she’s a huge influence. Mostly I’m just excited to be like as good as a mom as my mom. annotations:
You made the road
 Made the road one-way

This lyric uses the metaphor in the previous line to expand upon the theme of social stigma against “difficult” women. The attitudes of bigoted men, not seeing women as equals, creates the conditions for conflict when a woman asserts herself.

I’m only a figure if you can see my frame
 I’m only a figure if you can see my frame
 I’m only a figure if you can see my frame
Here, the woman is only recognized as a person (see: “figure”) if they allow others to see their body (see: “frame”). In many societies, a woman’s worth is tied to their sexuality.

I’m only a struggle if I get in your way
 I’m only a struggle if I get in your way
 I’m only a struggle if I get in your way

Women who refuse to belittle themselves or their presence for men are often called “difficult” or “a struggle” for their lack of immediate cooperation. If things had gone the other way, if the speaker were to keep their head down and let the men in their life walk all over them, they would never have been deemed “a struggle.”

I’m only a woman if woman is a word
 I’m only a woman if woman is a word
 I’m only a woman if woman is a word

There are a lot of dualities and dependencies (“I’m this-if that”) happening within this song. The picture of the pure, small, skinny (yet curvy), cis, hairless, meek, subservient thing attached to conventional notions of womanhood is vain and misrepresentative of reality; yet these stigmas shape what a woman is perceived to be in mainstream society.

If being a woman means adhering to the above criteria, the singer herself would not be considered a woman. She could only be a woman if “woman” was only a word, detached from all social connotations and expectations.

I’m only a woman if woman is a word
 I’m only a woman if woman is a word
 I’m only a woman if woman is a word

There are a lot of dualities and dependencies (“I’m this-if that”) happening within this song. The picture of the pure, small, skinny (yet curvy), cis, hairless, meek, subservient thing attached to conventional notions of womanhood is vain and misrepresentative of reality; yet these stigmas shape what a woman is perceived to be in mainstream society.

If being a woman means adhering to the above criteria, the singer herself would not be considered a woman. She could only be a woman if “woman” was only a word, detached from all social connotations and expectations.

I’m always coming on the inside
 I’m always coming on the inside
 I’m always coming on the inside
 When you’re coming
 When you’re coming on the outside

In its most literal sense, this lyric is simply about the differences in the ways men and women experience orgasm. Whereas most women’s orgasms are not outwardly visible (“coming on the inside”), considering female ejaculation is a general rarity, men’s orgasms are obvious because they ejaculate and the cum is visible (“coming on the outside”).

It also appears to be a commentary on the way sexuality is meant to be expressed by each gender in the eyes of the general public. Stereotypically, while women are raised to hide their sexuality, lest they be shamed and labeled whores, men are not only expected but encouraged to be outwardly sexual.

Bird to a bee
 Bird to a bee
 Bird to a bee

“Birds and the bees” is a term used to describe the point during which a child learns about sexual intercourse. The “bird” is meant to represent female ovulation, since birds lay eggs, while “bees” represent male fertilization, since they pollinate flowers.

Here, Empress Of calls out the notion that women’s status in society is directly proportional to that of their husbands or male relatives, a concept which has existed since early on in history. Calling any woman “the [blank] of a man” instead of by name strips her of her essential humanity, implying that she lacks worth without a connection to a man.

I’m only an image of what you see
 I’m only an image of what you see
 I’m only an image of what you see
 You don’t know me
 You don’t know me
 You don’t know me

This first verse is about individual perceptions. She’s saying that what people see is a subjective experience; that each person comes to their own biased conclusions and judgments (for better or worse) about others based upon their own individual perceptions, none of which has to do with who the person really is, unless you truly know them on a personal level. It’s about projecting onto others your own relativistic views about them.
